Reasoning: The claim that MEK inhibitors are not effective in RAS-driven mouse models of cancer is refuted by multiple studies. Paper 33924486 (Credibility: 2.0/5, in_vitro/animal_study) demonstrates that dual MEK and ERK inhibition reduced tumor growth and increased progression-free survival in Kras-driven genetically engineered mouse models of NSCLC and PDAC. Specifically, it mentions "Dual MEK inhibitor plus ERK inhibitor therapy shows anti-tumor efficacy in an HrasG12V-driven autochthonous sarcoma model." Paper 51889704 (Credibility: 2.5/5, animal_study) shows that combination PI3K/MEK inhibition induced tumor regression in a mouse model of PIK3CA wild-type, KRAS mutant colorectal cancer. Furthermore, paper 22872574 (Credibility: 2.3/5, animal_study) found that combined treatment with a MEK inhibitor (AZD6244) and a PI3K/mTOR inhibitor (BEZ235) exhibited significant antitumor activity, including marked tumor regression and improved survival, in a RAS-driven melanoma GEMM and other breast cancer models. While some of these studies involve combination therapies rather than MEK inhibitors alone, they clearly demonstrate the effectiveness of MEK inhibition in RAS-driven mouse models when appropriately combined, directly contradicting the claim of general ineffectiveness.
